  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and conventions against money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) - An international organization that sets standards and promotes policies to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n2. United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime - Provides a framework for international cooperation against organized crime, including money laundering.\n\n3. The Palermo Convention - Requires member states to criminalize money laundering and establish preventive measures.\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision - Provides guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering.\n\n5. Many countries have their own domestic laws, like the U.S. Bank Secrecy Act and Anti-Money Laundering (AML) regulations.\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement internal compliance programs\n\nMost developed countries have similar anti-money laundering regulations aimed at detecting and preventing financial crimes.",
